programme.title: Live One-Day International Cricket
programme.desc: Windies v England. Coverage of the fourth match in the five-match series from National Cricket Stadium in St George's. The only previous scheduled one-dayer between the sides at this venue was abandoned back in 2004, and it has not hosted a match in this format at all since August 2014. The Windies will perhaps be glad to return here though, as they have won their last five 50-over matches at this ground, albeit all against limited opposition in Zimbabwe and Bangladesh.(n)

programme.desc: A look at some of the greatest milestones ever recorded in sport, focussing on the age-related accomplishments of Pele, Bernard Hopkins and Marc Marquez. Pele made a name for himself when he represented Brazil in the 1958 FIFA World Cup, becoming the youngest player to appear in the tournament when aged 17 years and 249 days. Hopkins held multiple world boxing titles, and continued his professional career into his 50s, while Marquez became the youngest rider to win the MotoGP World Championship when he claimed his first title in 2013.(n)

programme.desc: Miami Dolphins v San Diego Chargers. A review of the AFC Championship Game played in 1982, which came to be known as the `epic in Miami'. The Chargers started the first quarter in scintillating form, and raced to a 24-0 lead that appeared to have settled the contest in their favour early on. However, The Dolphins battled back in the second quarter, scoring 17 unanswered points to narrow the margin, and at the end of the fourth quarter the teams were tied at 38-38. Despite the extreme heat and humidity, and with many players suffering the effects of dehydration, it took a further 14 minutes of overtime before San Diego kicked a winning field goal to eventually claim a 41-28 victory, and progress to the Super Bowl.(n)
